adjectives.description: myall (comparative more myall, superlative most myall)

entries.meaning: (Australia) According to Aboriginal tradition; traditionally indigenous. [from 19th c.]
examples: It was some kind of gadget that can take away all your myall words, transcribe what you say in better language so people can understand what you are talking about.

entries.meaning: (obsolete, Australian Aboriginal) A stranger; an ignorant person.
examples: He  […]  flung himself into the outstretched arms of Anna. "Wazzer madder liddle man?" she crooned. "Aw wazzer madder wid de liddle myall now?"

entries.meaning: (Australia) An Aborigine living according to tradition.

description: Aboriginal, perhaps a transferred use of Etymology 1, above.

entries.meaning: Any of various Australian acacias, especially the weeping myall, Acacia pendula, or the wood of such trees.
examples: Friday, 30th December, Hanson Range. […] Changed our course to a very prominent hill (which I have named Mount Arthur) bearing 275 degrees, and after crossing two small myall creeks and a stony plain with salt bush and grass, at ten miles we struck a large myall and gum creek, coming from the north-west, with some very deep channels.
